 <title>Community Blog Series: Affinegy</title>
 <link>https://identity.allseenalliance.org/news/blogs/2015/04/community-blog-series-affinegy</link>
 <description>
		&lt;span class=&quot;a2a_kit a2a_target addtoany_list&quot; id=&quot;da2a_9&quot;&gt;
			&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_facebook&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_twitter&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_google_plus&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_dd addtoany_share_save&quot; href=&quot;http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=https%3A%2F%2Fidentity.allseenalliance.org%2Fnews%2Fblogs%2F2015%2F04%2Fcommunity-blog-series-affinegy&amp;amp;title=Blogs%20-%20AllSeen%20Alliance&quot;&gt; Share&lt;/a&gt;
		&lt;/span&gt;
		
		
  &lt;div class=&quot;field-body view-mode-rss&quot;&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://allseenalliance.org/sites/default/files/member_logos/member_comm_affinegy.jpg&quot; style=&quot;float:left; height:140px; margin:5px; width:200px&quot; /&gt;Since 2003, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.affinegy.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Affinegy&lt;/a&gt; has delivered connected device management solutions to leading cable/telco broadband service providers and device manufacturers that help consumers customers with installation, provisioning, management and support of services.  Now, Affinegy’s software enables full, easy, secure device connectivity in the Internet of Things.  Affinegy is a leader in the AllSeen Alliance, the broadest cross-industry consortium to advance the Internet of Things.  Affinegy is headquartered in Austin, TX with additional offices in Dallas, and Wroclaw, Poland.  &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Why did you join the AllSeen Alliance?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;As a 2003 era pioneer in a software platform that transformed unruly WiFi connection problems into a profitable managed service opportunity, we at Affinegy leaped early and became a founding and active member of the AllSeen Alliance. We viewed AllJoyn as the ideal protocol and a key component of the digital glue that makes the Internet of Things “just work.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What does your company hope to achieve through its participation in the Alliance?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Through the Alliance, Affinegy aims to multiply the number of partners, customers, and suppliers we have that are united in desire and action to work to create interoperable products and services that are at the root of this Internet of Things market inflection.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What contributions is your company making, or is considering making, to the project?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Affinegy is playing several active roles in the Alliance. Art Lancaster, Affinegy’s CTO, is entering his second year of service as a Community Director of the AllSeen Alliance Board. He also chairs the &lt;a href=&quot;https://wiki.allseenalliance.org/gateway/gatewayagent&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Gateway Working Group&lt;/a&gt; and is a Member of the Technical Steering Committee. Josh Spain, Director of Engineering at Affinegy, serves on the Technical Interface Review Board. Melissa Simpler serves on the Marketing Committee and is heavily engaged in the Tradeshow/Events Marketing Working Group. Affinegy is also contributing code via the Gateway Working Group and providing quality assurance resources to ensure the code of this working group is high quality and built for performance, security, and scale.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Can you describe the Internet of Everything? Can you help us understand how our homes and business might function 10 years from now because of AllJoyn and the Alliance?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Internet of Everything is the biggest market and technology inflection the world has seen since the Internet. Gartner, in their November 2013 Forecast report on IoT, reports that the number of connected things (excluding computers, tablets, and mobile phones) will grow 30-fold from 0.9 billion units in 2009 to 26 billion units by 2020. Further, that the total cost of a basic microcontroller, Bluetooth connectivity and a simple sensor (temperature, vibration or acceleration), will approach $1 by 2020. Cost will no longer be a barrier to commercialization. Look no further than Amazon’s latest IoT product announcement, AmazonDash, to see evidence. Brands, large and small, will all connect anything and everything to the Internet, their users and their products – those that cost just a few dollars to those that cost many thousand dollars. These connections will fuel “always connected” social behavior and demand for Cloud and interconnected Cloud services. New information exchange and data mining/analytics markets will be birthed to make life or work activities more predictive, automated, and convenient. Hopefully the automation will free us as humans to be more productive and creative in higher orders of thinking and doing, and hopefully we will not trend toward the world imagined in the Sci-Fi movie, Wall-e.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The AllSeen Alliance is at the heart of these changes. The Alliance drives widespread adoption of the Internet of Everything through its leading and key interoperable peer connectivity and communications framework based on AllJoyn that hundreds of member companies are contributing to and planning to incorporate into their products.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Why is open source software and collaborative development important for advancing the Internet of Everything?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The ubiquity of the Internet grew largely through open source and open standards like Netscape, HTML, Apache and Linux.  We believe this same success of open source is foundation of achieving broad interoperability in the Internet of Things. The truly open and “code first” core of the Alliance achieves speed to market and best of breed products in market. All the work of the AllSeen Alliance is fully open and available to everyone – no requirement to join until you want to contribute to the project’s technical direction. .  Critical learning from early deployments brings user feedback back into the design and development process very rapidly to drive responsive improvements. The collaborative working group structure of the Alliance brings together members from within the Alliance to work on common objectives. The diversity of the members ensures that the protocol comprehensively serves multiple and wide-ranging market needs.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How will the work of the AllSeen Alliance impact the industry in the short term? In the long term?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;AllSeen Alliance is the leading contender to bring global Internet of Everything interoperability, robust security and compatibility across the broadest number and range of brands’ services and things. &lt;a href=&quot;https://allseenalliance.org/showcase&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Products are already in market today&lt;/a&gt;, including LG Smart TVs, LIFX light bulbs, Musaic  HiFi sound, Fon’s Gramofon, and more. The membership base has grown from a base of 20 to over 150 companies in just 16 months with that growth trend continuing and even increasing.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;/div&gt;
</description>
